Marc-Andre Fleury celebrated his day with the Stanley Cup on Saturday.
His time in Pittsburgh has already come to an official end, having been selected by Vegas in the expansion draft. He‚Äôs already said ‚Äòthank-you‚Äô to the fans of Pittsburgh, but the events of this weekend, in his mind it seems, close the chapter for good on this stage of his career.
‚ÄúI think this was my last day as a Penguin, I would say,‚Äù Fleury told NHL.com.
‚ÄúI have members of my family who had their Penguins hats who told me this was the last time those will come out. So I think after today, I can turn the page and get ready for Vegas.‚Äù
The former first overall pick captured three Stanley Cup rings with the Penguins. While he wasn‚Äôt the No. 1 goalie last year ‚Äî or in the 2017 final, either ‚Äî he played a significant role in Pittsburgh‚Äôs success through the first half of this year‚Äôs playoff before Matt Murray returned from injury.
He earned praise for how he handled the situation toward the end in Pittsburgh. After the final, reports surfaced he had agreed to waive his no-movement clause, which left him exposed in the expansion draft.
At age 32, he still has two more years left on his current contract, with an annual cap hit of $5.75 million. He‚Äôll no doubt garner plenty of attention this upcoming season as the experienced starter on the Golden Knights‚Äô roster.
But Saturday was for Fleury to enjoy one last championship won with the Penguins.


